** Introduction

*Summary*

Bootstrap is a framework for CSS
It's primarily used for _responsive design_

It divides the page by 12 columns going down horizontally & uses this for it's calculations/functions
It doesn't use rows, as a web page can keep going down infinitely

*How to use*

Create a <div> in html & give it the tag class="row" or class="col-md"

row -> sets up the container in it's own grid row
col-md-4 -> column-medium_screens-4_of_12_grid_columns
            So, col-md-4 means a column for medium screens which takes up 4/12 width of the screen

If you overlap the 12 columns it will move the row down to accommodate
But as a rule, don't do more than 12 widths

** Grid System

As there are 12 columns in Bootstrap, if I add 1 element, it will take up the whole page width ways
If I had 6 elements, they would each take up 2 of the 12 columns

As the page is resized, this elements will always be resized to remain to be 2/12 width or 6/12 width of the page

Bootstrap allows us to select what data will be displayed based on the screen size provided

| Class    | Screen Size | Grid Behaviour               | Container Width | Suitable For       |
|          |             |                              |                 |                    |
| .col-    | Extra small | Horizontal at all times      | None (auto)     | Portrait phones    |
| .col-sm  | Small       | Collapsed to start           | 540px           | Landscape phones   |
|          |             | Horizontal above breakpoints |                 |                    |
| .col-md- | Medium      | " "                          | 720px           | Tablets            |
| .col-lg- | Large       | " "                          | 960px           | Laptops            |
| .col-xl- | Extra Large | " "                          | 1140px          | Laptops & Desktops |

** Key Concepts

1. *Col*
   Keyword stands for "column"
   This is how Bootstrap identifies elements as part of the grid structure
2. *sm/md/lg/xl*
   These define screen size breakpoints
   This allows the layout to adapt to different devices
3. ***
   Represents the number of columns a block spans (out of 12)
   12 = full-width
   6 = half the row
   3 = a quarter of the row
   
   Although the columns are limited to 12, there can be an unlimited number of rows (as a web page can go down indefinitely)
   I.e. you can make infinite number of elements that work down a page but 1 row is 1 section of the page horizontally, split vertically 12 times
   
** Structure

Bootstrap doesn't care what HTML element has the class
So, container, row & column can be added to any element (body, section, div, etc...)

<div class="container">
   <div class="row">

      <div class="col-md-4">
         <code for what goes in this row for the first 1/3 of the horizontal row
      </div>
         
      <div class="col-md-8">
         <code for the next 2/3>
      </div>

   </div>
</div>

